			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-style: italic">I'm going to make a wild guess at what the Vision(tm) of the Mage class is and then make an even wilder suggestion based on my understanding.  Hold on, it'll be a fun ride. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" /></span>
<br />

<br />
Let's face it, mage pets are not really that far superior to other pets, especially beastlord warders.  But SoE maintains that the mage class centers around its pets.  It has been said that though mage pets are not vastly superior in DPS or tankability, there are different pets available to mages that are useful in different situations, and THAT is what makes mages the premium pet class.
<br />

<br />
I believe SoE intended the 4 mage pets to be better than other pets at specific tasks, yet be specialized to the point that they loose out in other departments.  Take the high end water pet for example... highest available pet DPS (other than charm), but he has low HPs to compensate.  But the HPs aren't an issue if you use him in the right situation, grouping with somebody to tank for him.  That's kind of obvious, but I just threw it out there as an example.
<br />

<br />
Since SoE historically likes to uphold the Vision(tm), I propose the following changes to improve the mage class while keeping in line with the idea that mage pets are superior through specialization, not overall power.
<br />

<br />
I can think of 4 thinks everyone wants in a group:
<br />
Tanking, DPS, healing, and utility.
<br />

<br />
And what a coincidence!  We have 4 types of pets!  What if, and this is a big, far out there, IF, our pets could fill these roles in a small way?
<br />

<br />
Tanking:  Eath pet could have its tanking ability increased IMENSELY to the point that it is a viable tank in all but raid situations.  Put it under knight tanking, with DPS also under that of knights.
<br />

<br />
DPS:  Fire pet could fill this role nicely.  Give it huge melee DPS, not just from behind.  Also let it cast a good fire nuke that is not mana dependant.  Give it low enough HPs that high end stuff will easilly one-round it.
<br />

<br />
Healing:  Water is widely associated with healing.  Give the water pet a limited healing ability coupled with below-average (shaman pet-ish) melee output.  This way it could serve as a crappy patch healer.  Who would it heal?  I'm torn on if this should be group memeber, or other pets.  Think of it as the cleric of the pet world, keeping everybody's pets alive through those nasty AEs!
<br />

<br />
Utility:  Leave air pets alone.  Let them keep their stun (useful in many ways) and their current melee status.  They are the balanced pet similar to other classes, but with the added utility of their stun.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
